        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px;">Is there a movement behind Greenlandic independence?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">In his New Year's address, the Greenlandic prime minister stated that it was about time Greenland became independent from its colonizer. While the island of 57,000 people has been a self-governing territory since 1979, it has had the right to <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-01-2025-bq1-14-independence-by-referendum" target="_blank">independence by referendum</a> since 2009. Greenland holds elections this year, so a motion to referendum could be on the ballot. The movement for Greenlandic independence is not a new subject. Public support is strong, with <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-01-2025-bq2-15-a-2019-poll" target="_blank">a 2019 poll</a> showing that just under 70% of Greenland's adult population favor independence. In April 2023, a constitutional commission presented Greenland‚Äôs parliament, the island‚Äôs first draft constitution. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Historical grievances and social disparities have fueled independence movements for years. Many of their <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-01-2025-bq3-16-modernization-efforts" target="_blank">modernization efforts</a> and sweeping changes ended up stripping Greenlanders of elements of their culture, such as hunting and fishing. Greenlandic children were involuntarily sent to Denmark to become ‚Äúbetter citizens.‚Äù A <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-01-2025-bq4-17-forced-birth-control" target="_blank">forced birth control</a> campaign in the 1960s still holds the last harm on some women today. Greenlanders are also incarcerated around <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-01-2025-bq5-18-3-times-more" target="_blank">3 times more</a> than someone from the rest of the Nordic region.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">While there are noticeable discrepancies between Greenlanders and Danes, Greenland has benefitted some from being a subject of Denmark. Greenland is rich in mineral, oil, and natural gas resources but relies on annual subsidies from Denmark worth some $515.3 million a year. There is the discussion that they could make a fortune off their resources without Denmark‚Äôs help, but they would still have to depend on Denmark for some infrastructure. Denmark changed its coat of arms this week, indicating it wants to maintain its hold on Greenland and the Faroe Islands. But it‚Äôs the Greenlandic citizens who will decide how they want to direct their future.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
